WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.520
You've got the sales skills down.

2
00:00:03.155 --> 00:00:07.875
Now we need to talk about how the team
actually communicates and works together day to

3
00:00:07.875 --> 00:00:12.675
day. Because it doesn't matter how good your
calls are if the rest of the team doesn't

4
00:00:12.675 --> 00:00:14.485
know what's happening with your leads.

5
00:00:14.960 --> 00:00:18.400
At the BMH Group, Slack is the command
center.

6
00:00:18.840 --> 00:00:21.080
Sandra is where your leads and data live.

7
00:00:21.720 --> 00:00:27.740
Slack is where decisions happen, where approvals
flow, and where the team stays in sync.

8
00:00:28.640 --> 00:00:31.220
We organize Slack by county.

9
00:00:31.760 --> 00:00:33.380
Every market has its own channel.

10
00:00:33.900 --> 00:00:36.380
Jackson County, Clay County, St.

11
00:00:36.480 --> 00:00:40.860
Louis County, Montgomery County, Camden
County, and so on.

12
00:00:41.040 --> 00:00:45.680
When you're working a lead in Jackson County,
anything about that lead gets discussed in

13
00:00:45.680 --> 00:00:47.020
the Jackson County channel.

14
00:00:47.520 --> 00:00:49.940
This keeps everything organized by
geography.

15
00:00:50.360 --> 00:00:55.240
If someone needs to see what's happening in
a specific market, they know exactly where

16
00:00:55.240 --> 00:00:55.740
to look.

17
00:00:56.740 --> 00:01:01.960
When you draft an outbound text or email to
a seller, it goes through an approval

18
00:01:01.960 --> 00:01:03.800
process before it gets sent.

19
00:01:04.298 --> 00:01:07.441
You write the draft and post it in the
appropriate county channel.

20
00:01:07.820 --> 00:01:09.060
Your manager reviews it.

21
00:01:09.220 --> 00:01:11.700
They either approve it or ask for changes.

22
00:01:12.280 --> 00:01:15.500
Once it's approved, you send it through
Dialpad or Gmail.

23
00:01:16.780 --> 00:01:21.980
Every message that goes out to a seller
represents the BMH Group, so we want the tone,

24
00:01:22.440 --> 00:01:24.780
the content, and the timing to be right.

25
00:01:25.220 --> 00:01:27.459
Early on, you'll go through this on
everything.

26
00:01:27.780 --> 00:01:32.600
As you build trust and demonstrate solid
judgment, the process speeds up.

27
00:01:32.740 --> 00:01:35.360
But it always exists as a quality check.

28
00:01:36.140 --> 00:01:41.660
When a lead gets serious, when it's moving
through discovery and heading toward a

29
00:01:41.660 --> 00:01:46.160
handoff, use threads in Slack to keep the
discussion organized.

30
00:01:46.780 --> 00:01:48.320
Tag the relevant team members.

31
00:01:48.920 --> 00:01:55.180
Something like, lead ready for handoff,
Diane Weber, Dayton duplex, full notes

32
00:01:55.180 --> 00:02:01.120
in Sandra, summary, tired landlord, 11
years, behind on taxes,

33
00:02:01.640 --> 00:02:04.320
wants out before fall, very motivated.

34
00:02:04.320 --> 00:02:09.460
That kind of post gives everyone immediate
context without having to go dig through the

35
00:02:09.460 --> 00:02:15.920
CRM. Threads keep deal specific conversations
contained so they don't get buried in

36
00:02:15.920 --> 00:02:17.340
the general channel flow.

37
00:02:18.140 --> 00:02:22.980
When a lead moves to stage four and you're
doing the handoff, make sure everything is

38
00:02:22.980 --> 00:02:24.340
pushed to Sandra first.

39
00:02:24.860 --> 00:02:30.680
Complete seller profile, all your discovery
notes, a motivation summary, their timeline,

40
00:02:31.020 --> 00:02:37.300
property condition details, price expectations,
who the decision maker is, how and when

41
00:02:37.300 --> 00:02:42.540
they prefer to be contacted, and any
sensitivities or hot buttons the acquisition team

42
00:02:42.540 --> 00:02:43.460
should know about.

43
00:02:44.294 --> 00:02:49.294
Then post the handoff summary in Slack and
tag the acquisition team member who's picking

44
00:02:49.294 --> 00:02:54.834
it up. That dual communication, CRM data
plus Slack notification, make sure nothing

45
00:02:54.834 --> 00:02:56.025
falls through the cracks.

46
00:02:56.900 --> 00:03:03.100
When sellers respond to your texts or emails,
you log the response in Sandra immediately

47
00:03:03.100 --> 00:03:06.020
and post it in the appropriate county
channel.

48
00:03:06.340 --> 00:03:11.500
If the response needs attention, if the seller
is ready to move forward or has questions

49
00:03:11.500 --> 00:03:14.200
or raised an objection, tag the right
person.

50
00:03:14.460 --> 00:03:19.160
If it's something you can handle yourself,
like a simple follow-up or scheduling a

51
00:03:19.160 --> 00:03:21.820
callback, just handle it and log it.

52
00:03:22.560 --> 00:03:24.620
We do daily standups in Slack.

53
00:03:25.160 --> 00:03:31.060
Keep them short, how many dials you made,
any standout conversations, leads that moved

54
00:03:31.060 --> 00:03:35.560
stages or got handed off, anything you're
stuck on, and what you're planning for

55
00:03:35.560 --> 00:03:37.680
tomorrow. Three to five lines.

56
00:03:38.120 --> 00:03:42.740
That's it. Your manager and the team review
these to stay aligned on what's happening

57
00:03:42.740 --> 00:03:43.660
across the board.

58
00:03:44.520 --> 00:03:50.060
If you hit a situation you're not sure how
to handle, whether it's a tricky objection,

59
00:03:50.600 --> 00:03:55.800
an unusual property, a seller asking about
something you haven't seen before, don't

60
00:03:55.800 --> 00:03:58.760
guess. Post in Slack and tag your manager.

61
00:03:59.340 --> 00:04:04.480
Something like, have a seller in KC asking
about selling while in Chapter 13 bankruptcy.

62
00:04:05.158 --> 00:04:06.301
Not sure how to proceed.

63
00:04:06.740 --> 00:04:08.760
Notes in Sandra under their name.

64
00:04:08.760 --> 00:04:12.520
Then keep working your other leads while you
wait for guidance.

65
00:04:13.360 --> 00:04:17.360
It is always better to ask than to give a
seller wrong information.

66
00:04:18.180 --> 00:04:18.520
Always.

67
00:04:20.280 --> 00:04:22.420
A few things about how we operate as a team.

68
00:04:23.540 --> 00:04:27.960
Overcommunicate. If you're not sure whether
something is worth sharing in Slack, share

69
00:04:27.960 --> 00:04:33.000
it anyway. It's better to have too much
information flowing than not enough.

70
00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:37.660
When someone tags you, respond within the
hour during work hours.

71
00:04:38.080 --> 00:04:39.760
Keep everything professional.

72
00:04:40.260 --> 00:04:43.680
Slack is a work tool, not a group chat with
friends.

73
00:04:45.100 --> 00:04:50.780
And when something good happens, when a deal
closes, when someone has a great call, when

74
00:04:50.780 --> 00:04:56.400
a lead finally converts after weeks of
follow up, post it, celebrate it.

75
00:04:56.660 --> 00:05:00.520
Wins build momentum for the whole team, not
just the person who got the deal.

76
00:05:01.600 --> 00:05:04.200
That's how the BMH Group works day to day.

77
00:05:04.620 --> 00:05:10.300
Your leads live in the CRM, your communication
lives in Slack, your calls go through

78
00:05:10.300 --> 00:05:14.700
Dialpad, and the whole team stays connected
through those three systems.

79
00:05:15.340 --> 00:05:19.320
Learn the flow, follow the process, and
you'll fit right in.

80
00:05:20.240 --> 00:05:23.140
Alright, that wraps up your day to day
playbook.

81
00:05:23.620 --> 00:05:28.680
Your roleplay for this section is an elderly
seller in Dayton whose adult son is opposed

82
00:05:28.680 --> 00:05:33.940
to the sale. You'll need to navigate family
dynamics with patience and earn trust from

83
00:05:33.940 --> 00:05:39.940
both of them. When you're done, there's one
more stop where this role can take you.
